result.execSummary:
The defendant Gregory S Osborn was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Criminal Trespass to Dwelling, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.14(2).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant, Gregory S Osborn appeared with Attorney Samuel Louis Lawton.  Attorney Angeline E Winton appeared for the State.

8:14 a.m. Court calls case and recites appearances. Attorney Winton motion in limine about testimony about prior convictions then the State be allowed to impeach him on those convictions. Attorney Lawton objects to prejudicial and relevance. Court goes over convictions. Attorney Winton makes argument re: most current convictions are relevant to the case law; older convictions do lack relevance. Attorney Winton makes statement re: ask DE if he has been convicted of prior convictions and how many; if DE answers truthfully that will be all. Court questions State. Attorney Winton recites overview of case. Attorney Lawton agrees with the Court's analysis. Court agrees in part with Attorney Lawton. Court rules the older cases in Chippewa Co do not need to be counted in the amount of convictions. Attorney Winton raises the issue of witness and prior conviction history. Attorney Lawton objects to relevance. Court rules that the State cannot ask the witness about prior convictions. Attorney Winton makes statement re: two witnesses and one since has changed her name. Attorney Lawton makes statement re: one witness, possibly two. Court goes over proposed introduction with counsel. Counsel agrees. Attorney Winton makes statement re: text messages being brought up and may need to have discussion outside the presence of the jury. It will be taken up at that time. Attorney Winton requests if sequesteration of witnesses, Officer Bos remain as the Court Officer. Attorney Lawton does not plan to sequester witnesses. Attorney Winton is going to ask for sequester of witnesses. Court so orders. 8:31 a.m. Recess.

8:40 a.m. Jurors are seated.

8:43 a.m. Back on record. Court calls case and appearances. Court introduces himself and makes statement to jurors. Court introduces counsel, parties and witnesses. 8:46 a.m. Recess for Attorney Lawton to get witness. Attorney Lawton cannot find witness at this time. Attorney Lawton is to call witness back.  

8:51 a.m. Back on record. Court will proceed. Clerk swears in jurors. Court questions jurors. Juror Fogelberg makes statement. Juror Hare makes statement. Juror Hare makes statement. Juror Hare is excused. Juror Morris is called. Juror Scott makes statement. Juror Anderson makes statement. Juror Dinga makes statement. Juror Daniels makes statement. Juror Normand makes statement. Juror Miller makes statement. Juror Normand makes statement. Attorney Lawton interjects; witness has arrived. Court introduces witness. Court continues questioning jurors. Juror Miller makes statement. Attorney Winton questions jurors. Juror Dunbar makes statement. Juror Daniels makes statement. Juror Thompson makes statement. Juror Normand makes statement. Attorney Lawton does not have any questions for the juror.
Counsel strikes jurors. Court calls selected jurors. No objection to swearing in jurors from counsel. Clerk swears in jurors. Court gives jurors the jury instructions. 9:28 a.m. Recess. 

Back on the record at 9:51 Jury returns.  State begins opening statement.  Atty Lawton gives opening statement.  State calls Sara Ann Raimann to the stand. Clerks swears in witness. State begins questioning.  Objection by Atty Lawton. State continues questioning. Objection from Atty Lawton.  State continues questioning.  Nothing further from the state. Cross from Atty Lawton.  Nothing further from Atty Lawton.  Redirect from the state.  Nothing further. Recross. Nothing further. Redirect. Witness excused.  State calls Sgt. Dave Bos to the stand. Clerk swears in Sgt. Bos.   State begins questioning.  Nothing further from the state. Cross from Atty Lawton.  Nothing further. Redirect.  Nothing further.  State rests.    Atty Lawton calls Liz McLellen to the stand.  Clerk swears in Ms. McLellen. Atty Lawton begins questioning.  Nothing further from Atty Lawton.  Cross from the state. Redirect. Recross. Nothing further.  Witness excused.   Jury stands down. Court questions the defendant re: his right to testify.   Court finds the def. freely and knowingly making the decision to testify.  Back on record at 11:25  Jury returns.  Atty Lawton calls Gregory Osborn to the stand.  Clerk swears in witness.  Atty Lawton begins questioning.  Atty  Lawton offers exhibit 2-received.  Nothing further.  Cross from the state.  Objection from Atty Lawton. Over ruled, state continues questioning. Nothing further from the State. Defense rests. Attorneys to be back by 12:50 p.m. Recess. 

12:55 p.m. Back on record outside the presence of the jurors. Court goes over instructions with counsel. Court goes over Attorney Lawtons objection re: speculation of key made from witness. 

1:05 p.m. Jurors are seated. Attorney Winton re-calls and questions Ms. Raimann. Ms. Raimann testifies. Attorney Lawton objects. Counsel meets at side bar. Attorney Winton continues questioning. Nothing from Attorney Lawton. Ms. Raimann is excused and steps down. Testimony is closed. 1:10 p.m. Jurors excused.

Back on record at 1:26. Jury returns. Court begins w/ Jury Instructions. State gives closing argument.  Atty Lawton give closing argument.   Rebuttal from the state. Court continues with jury instructions.  Clerk swears in bailiff.  Jury has the case.  Off record. 

Back on the record at 2:41. The jury has a verdict.  

VerdictGuilty 


State speaks re: sentencing, requesting probation and jail time. 

Atty Lawton speaks re: sentencing, requesting probation. 

State speaks to the court.  Defendant speaks to the court. 

Court sentences the defendant.

1 year probation + costs   No contact w/ the Victim Sara Raimann  Off record at 2:57pm.
